label: Comparing copies of Etzlaub's Rom-weg map (1500)

description.@value: Erhard Etzlaub's (1455?-1532) 'Rom-weg' is a single-sheet woodcut map of Central Europe, and one of the earliest European printed maps. It is also the earliest surviving printed road map, designed to assist pilgrims from northern Europe to reach Rome for the Christian jubilee year of 1500. There are 13 known surviving institutional examples of this map, and all of them are slightly different in their printed impressions. Thanks to IIIF, for the first time we are able to bring together 6 of these examples in order to compare them and form some opinions on the possible printing sequence of them.
